01:01:57,239 --> 01:01:59,863
But it wasn't like it is today, where there are huge teams.

1165
01:01:59,983 --> 01:02:02,185
It wasn't a cinematic production like it is today.

1166
01:02:02,786 --> 01:02:07,249
So I think that's one of the other factors that might make it harder to come up with a great game today,

1167
01:02:07,709 --> 01:02:10,411
is you've got so many different people that are involved.

1168
01:02:10,892 --> 01:02:15,795
And sometimes, you know, the best ideas are sort of that solitary inspiration

1169
01:02:16,175 --> 01:02:19,518
that may not make it through, you know, just by throwing... it's like a boy band, you know.

1170
01:02:19,558 --> 01:02:23,160
You can throw a lot of people together, it doesn't necessarily mean you're gonna end up with good music.

1171
01:02:23,680 --> 01:02:27,063
So sometimes it's just that one solo artist that pulls it off.

1172
01:02:28,924 --> 01:02:29,084
Yes.

1173
01:02:30,719 --> 01:02:33,320
Last one, I promise.

1174
01:02:33,820 --> 01:02:36,101
You spoke a lot about intentionality and the fact

1175
01:02:36,141 --> 01:02:40,524
that you made the game the way you wanted to feel.

1176
01:02:40,624 --> 01:02:42,805
And it was kind of like that sort of if we make it,

1177
01:02:42,845 --> 01:02:45,086
they will come type of experience.

1178
01:02:45,987 --> 01:02:46,727
And it is a great game.

1179
01:02:49,369 --> 01:02:54,414
I'm just wondering if you feel like with the industry becoming so big and so quickly, so rapidly,

1180
01:02:55,014 --> 01:03:00,740
if that ideology or that idea is being lost in a corporate sort of setting?

1181
01:03:01,061 --> 01:03:06,206
Or how do you, I'm just curious as to how you feel about where the direction that it is going.

1182
01:03:06,532 --> 01:03:09,653
Yeah, I think big companies kill all kinds of, you know, art.

1183
01:03:09,993 --> 01:03:12,674
So I think that's entirely a factor.

1184
01:03:12,814 --> 01:03:15,075
You know, there's so much money in this industry nowadays.

1185
01:03:15,115 --> 01:03:16,616
It just, it wasn't like that before.

1186
01:03:17,176 --> 01:03:18,997
So yeah, I think the pressures and tensions

1187
01:03:19,037 --> 01:03:20,037
are very different today.

1188
01:03:20,177 --> 01:03:21,838
And I think getting a good product out.

1189
01:03:22,538 --> 01:03:24,799
and getting something that's really life-changing

1190
01:03:24,919 --> 01:03:26,439
is a bigger challenge for companies.

1191
01:03:26,479 --> 01:03:28,280
They've gotta roll titles out,

1192
01:03:28,340 --> 01:03:29,740
they have to roll a certain number out,

1193
01:03:29,780 --> 01:03:31,341
they need to get a certain level of sales.

1194
01:03:32,161 --> 01:03:33,982
They get there thinking that's all about marketing

1195
01:03:34,042 --> 01:03:36,222
and a lot of times it's really no,

1196
01:03:36,503 --> 01:03:38,583
it's about impacting people with your product.

1197
01:03:39,063 --> 01:03:41,724
So, you know, same with the motion picture industry.

1198
01:03:41,744 --> 01:03:43,325
You know, that's why we see so many bad movies.

1199
01:03:44,105 --> 01:03:45,706
You don't just think, you sit there and just think,

1200
01:03:46,126 --> 01:03:48,787
wow, they put in so many millions of dollars and this is it?

1201
01:03:49,047 --> 01:03:50,487
You know, you think, what happened?

1202
01:03:50,827 --> 01:03:58,600
But it's that, it's an agenda, it's a corporate agenda and it can make getting artistic and really wonderful product out difficult.

1203
01:03:58,924 --> 01:04:02,026
Any suggestions as to something to say to those folks?

1204
01:04:02,046 --> 01:04:03,507
